commentBody:
@Nikita Richardson
You're back!
Love your writing style. Looking forward to more of it.

@SP

Another gin crosses the wine of 47A - is that a three drink example? 

(Including the double gin, or the rye in 60A, also makes an ENNEAD)

@Selective Walrus
Perhaps "sequence" would be more accurate? But, with the answer containing SCALE, it's a toss up.
And... 2-5-1... nice! Bill will be proud of your taste in music. I play primarily the ever-popular 1-4-5 progression.

@Senex Sr.
So....there were TWO villains.  
My problem was coming up with HECTOR ...which confusion did not last long, but tsk on me.....  LECTER was playing with the FBI agent--trading what he knew for personal information about her life.  That was villainous...  and then of course the kidnapper/murderer was even worse because he was NOT locked up...

@ad absurdum
neither is having an old friend for dinner.
chianti, anyone?

@patk

I'm glad someone else was confused by that!  

I am just now realizing that "Hawkeye" is the mascot of the University of Iowa.

@Jeb Jones
But then why are the Blackhawks playing for Chicago in the NHL?
I am confused about one of the few non-baseball sports facts that I know.

@SP
@Francis

"Gut" was ubiquitous slang on my campus in the 80's.  The origin of the phrase refers to a course gutted of all difficult content and exams, I think.

As a med student who hated the "memorize stuff on the supermarket shelves and regurgitate it back on an exam" approach to pre-clinical medical education, I can assure you anatomy was no gut.  Not for me, anyway.

@Francis

Me neither. I've just checked the etymology online and apparently nobody really has a clue how that siIIy term emerged. There are several alternative theories.

I would not have been able to complete this puzzle without remembering some stuff I have learned from previous puzzles, which sadly (I say this as an anti-capitalist) includes at least two brands...

@Heidi

Thank you for letting me know.
Now *I* don't feel so bad, lol!

@sotto voce

Sláinte!

(I’ve been watching a lot of Irish-themed Netflix shows!)

@BobSolo

It's also Scottish Gaelic and I can't believe I forgot that one. It's unforgivable because I just rewatched the full 8 seasons of Outlander!

I'm not much of a drinker, but next time we go over the TWO DRINK MINIMUM, I'll be sure to include that one. Thank you!

@D

So glad to know! You're most welcome.
I agree, her voice is the cat's meow. Gone too soon...

@CB,
My grandma used to say something to the effect of “everyone eats a peck of dirt in their lifetime”. In her case, it was more practical than philosophical - she might have just tumbled the biscuits onto the floor (but she still expected us to eat them!)
But a more recent reference (maybe a puzzle last week?) had me leaning toward DIET.

@Elena

Do yourself a favor and let go of the streak - it is a drug peddled to foster unhealthy engagement with the puzzles.

Also, especially if you're relatively new at this, have no qualms about looking stuff up. That's what I did daily when I was starting here 3 years ago. Over time, some of this stuff will just stick.

@Andrzej
This is what I call the barnacle theory of knowledge. If you're in the sea long enough, things just stick to you. 
Worked pretty well for me!

@Francis

Baby talk does that for me. Was it yesterday's puzzle that featured "Oopsie" for ERROR? 

Ick!

@Grumpy 
Arg! Auto correct turned "Hogwarts" into "Howards" multiple times, and I didn't catch at least one. (It also tried to make "arg", above, into "argue"). 

I wish it would at least highlight the "corrected" word, so that I was aware of the change!

@Steve L

Thanks!

I thought of it independently though so I'm still proud of my idea 😃

@Ed H.
“Five Easy Pieces” - 
“I’d like a chicken salad sandwich on toasted wheat, hold the chicken”

@Petrol

I get the compaint about CCCP, even if the answer was an instant gimme and I had no personal nit to pick with the clue. It would have been better to clue CCCP as the Russian, rather than Cyrillic, version of USSR, since that implies a different language rather than just a different alphabet.

The "head" thing is a perfect example how American crosswords sacrifice accuracy for a bit of flair and misdirection. Again, I get your complaint, but that's just how things work around here.

@Andrzej
@Petrol

The nit about a head being nautical and, therefore, not relevant is n't even a nit, I think.  It's more like a microbe.

Why should it matter where the bathroom is?

If the clue had been "Port-a-Potties of Hogwarts" LOOS would work, too.

@Petrol
I was trying to remember “Nearly Headless Nick”. Nick would’ve fit, except the clue was plural. 

Personally, I was glad to see “LOOS” for heads. Stumped me at first, but I (for one) don’t think of head (or heads) as strictly nautical.  I’ve often heard (particularly in male corporate vernacular) “I’m hittin’ the head before we leave”.  But apparently, the British equivalent may indeed be “hit the heads”.

@Phil
I meant to conclude with a good-natured smiley, but hit "submit" too fast--so here it is:

:-)

@Patrick J.
Yeah. Ma ami would be weird, wouldn't it?
Thanks for making me believe for a few minutes that my French (also sixty odd years old) is better than it really is.

@Peter
I learned TOWAWAY Zone from a song about street signs, on "The Electric Company," which was a kid's show. Not sure what I was supposed to do with that knowledge.

"Jane Street, Jones Street, Park Avenue..."

@Bill
You never disappoint.
Great write-up!

@Bill
Since posting that comment, I made a leisurely road trip between Detroit and Cleveland, and somewhere around Sandusky Bay, this came on my playlist--from the same shape-note tradition as my second clip, here played by Cordelia's Dad:
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eTAl8Cyxtg&list=RD4eTAl8Cyxtg&start_radio=1" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4eTAl8Cyxtg&list=RD4eTAl8Cyxtg&start_radio=1</a>

@Steve L

You know what I noticed?

Every time the Cubs played an away game, my comments got bumped. I noticed it happened each and every time I noticed it. That couldn't have been a coincidence.

@D
Seemed fine to me. Timed right between Tuesday best and average.
Seems to me that the clues mentioned in the column aren't always the 'tricky' ones--despite the heading-- but rather just clues the columnist feels like mentioning.

@Charles Peterson
Agree, I was a gnat’s asset under my Tuesday avg. Got close to a look-up, but persevered. 

Everyone experiences these differently. I was not at all in sync with constructors over the weekend, but on Monday had a PB.

@Monday
Some of the clues were sly, but most of this was either common knowledge, or gettable via the crossings, in my opinion...  

DeKalb County School District was big on testing students back in my day, and the 8th grade Homeroom teacher who had to administer one of the standardized tests did not know how to pronounce SERE in a sentence-completion test item.  I remember thinking how glad I was I didn't have her for English.  (I was behind enough as it was after Kg-7th grades in DoD schools and an overcrowded elementary public school. )  People do complain nowadays that schools lack the rigor that was experienced in the 50-60's...

@Xword Junkie

"A spicy on-line publication?"

[GIN]GE[RY E-][ZIN]E

@Times Rita
If you really only learned about s'mores from crossword puzzles, and not as a child sitting around a campfire, I pity you. OTOH, If you reached puzzle-solving age oblivious to acne, consider yourself lucky!

In any case, Yes, my mileage was similar to yours. As PENTATONIC SCALE and ENNEADS  began to appear from the crosses, I though--"really? on a Tuesday?" And "sere" is a word I use regularly in conversation, especially around late November.

@D
None of her words were unusual, IMHO.  
Maybe you are much younger than we are.  (I was appalled that Solon (Ohio) Schools did not emphasize vocabulary for HS students.  (My kids were there 90's-2001.)

@Mean Old  "Who needs desserts?"

Whaaaaaaa?

(S'mores are only messy if one attempts to prepare them indoors--and why? Outdoors, nothing a little creek water and Dr. Bronner's peppermint soap can't solve.)

@Mean Old Lady
We’re in mandatory water restrictions here in my part of NC. “Hand watering” is OK, but yesterday the “skeeters” were thick enough to take the hose from my hand. Despite the temp and humidity, I was in long sleeves and trousers, and they still found exposed areas to feast upon. 

Oh, yeah - enjoyed the puzzle as well.

@Grant

Reminds me of an old Luke Bryan song:

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YEq-cvq_cK4" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YEq-cvq_cK4</a>

@Helen Wright
It’s frozen yogurt. To which might be added optional forms of sucrose — “sprinkles”, M&Ms, Oreo crumbles, even (gag) gummy worms, etc., etc.

It requires a vivid imagination to see it as anything resembling yoghurt.

@Bill

PLOTINUS LIVES!!!
NeoPlatonist (After)Lives Matter!

@Barry 
Could it have been the country? Has anyone else posted using it?

Emus can't spell?

@Crevecoeur

You'll never find TCBY clued as an ice cream brand.  The Y stands for yogurt (originally, This Can't Be Yogurt; later The Country's Best Yogurt, due to a copyright issue).  They once had a much bigger footprint, but they've retrenched a good bit in the past few years.

I was scouring the grid for EDY'S because of your comment.

@Barry Ancona

So it is.  But I must have gotten it through crosses, because I wasn't expecting to find it.  (I found TCBY and stopped looking.)

But I'm surprised then, since EDY'S is supposed to be East Coast, and its counterpart, Dreyer's, West Coast, that Crevecoeur says it's not available near her in PA.  It was my understanding that between the two brands, the entire country was covered, a la Hellmann's and Best Foods mayonnaise.

@Vaer
I hadn't noticed! 
Remembering your help when I first started solving - thank you.

@max
AER is a bit of crosswordese that shows up regularly.

I also got SERE quickly -- I think it's pretty common in puzzles, too.

@sotto voce

